🚨 1. Patch Identification (Where it starts)
      ✔ A patch usually appears because of:
              👉  A security advisory from Red Hat (RHSA)
              👉  Internal security team alert
              👉  Vulnerability scan (e.g., OpenSSL, kernel CVE)
      👉 Example:
              Critical OpenSSL vulnerability announced
              Red Hat releases: RHSA-2026:xxxx

🌐 2. Where the Patch Actually Lives
        👉 Important concept:
               ✔ The patch is not in Satellite yet
        👉 It exists in:
               ✔ Red Hat CDN (online repositories)

🔄 3. Sync: Bringing Patch into Satellite
       * Sync = downloading content from Red Hat CDN into Satellite
          Step:1 Inside Content → Red Hat Repositories:
               * Expand the Product (e.g., Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8)
                   ✔ Find required repos:
                         * BaseOS RPMs
                         * AppStream RPMs
                   ✔ Toggle them to Enabled
                   ✔ Click Save
         step:2  Go to Sync Screen
                👉 Navigate to: Content → Sync Status
                   ✔ You will see a list of:
                        * Products
                        * Repositories under each product
                        * Last sync status
                👉 This is the only place where sync is triggered

         Step 3 — Select Exact Repository
                👉 In Sync Status:
                       * Expand the Product
                       * Locate the exact repository, for example: RHEL 8 for x86_64 – BaseOS RPMs
                       * Select that specific repository


       * Includes:
           >> RPM packages
           >> Errata (patch metadata like RHSA, RHBA)
           >> Dependency info

        🧩 What Happens During Sync
                  Red Hat CDN
                       ↓
                  Satellite downloads:
                       ✔ New RPMs
                       ✔ New errata (RHSA)
                       ✔ Metadata
                       ↓
                  Stored in "Library"

        📊 What You See After Sync
                After sync completes: 
                  ✔  New errata appears in:  Content → Errata
                      Example:
                          RHSA-2026:1234 (OpenSSL fix)
                 then You can inspect:
                     * Severity (Critical/Important)
                     * Affected packages
                     * CVEs
🧠 Observe:
        Red Hat releases patch
                ↓
        Satellite syncs it
                ↓
        Patch sits in Library (waiting)
